            <section class="prose">
              <h2>How this Montana income tax calculator works</h2>
              <p>
                This tool estimates your Montana state income tax using a
                progressive bracket system, an approximate standard deduction by
                filing status, optional itemized deductions, and any Montana tax
                credits you enter.
              </p>
              <p>
                It is designed for quick planning and education. For filing your
                actual return, always refer to the official
                <a
                  href="https://revenue.mt.gov/taxes/individual-income-tax/"
                  target="_blank"
                  rel="noopener"
                  >Montana Department of Revenue guidance</a
                >
                and current MT tax tables.
              </p>

              <h3>1. Montana taxable income</h3>
              <p>
                We start from the income you enter as “Montana taxable income
                before deductions”, then adjust for Montana additions or
                subtractions and subtract your deduction:
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p>
                  <strong>MT adjusted income</strong> = Income before deductions
                  + MT additions/subtractions
                </p>
                <p>
                  <strong>MT taxable income</strong> = max(0, MT adjusted income
                  − deduction)
                </p>
              </div>
              <p>
                Additions/subtractions let you approximate Montana-specific
                adjustments (for example, interest on certain municipal bonds,
                or subtractions for some pensions). Enter negative numbers for
                subtractions.
              </p>

              <h3>2. Standard vs. itemized deductions (simplified)</h3>
              <p>
                Montana law uses a percentage-of-income standard deduction with
                minimum and maximum limits. To keep the calculator fast and
                user-friendly, we approximate this with flat standard deduction
                amounts by filing status (similar to federal rules).
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  If you choose <strong>Standard deduction</strong>, the
                  calculator uses an internal table by filing status and year.
                </li>
                <li>
                  If you choose <strong>Itemized deduction</strong>, we use the
                  dollar amount you enter instead.
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                This is usually close for most taxpayers, but high- or
                low-income filers should confirm with the official Montana
                instructions or a tax professional.
              </p>

              <h3>3. Montana tax brackets and marginal rate</h3>
              <p>
                Montana uses a progressive income tax: lower portions of your
                income are taxed at lower rates, and higher portions at higher
                rates.
              </p>
              <p>
                The calculator applies the appropriate bracket schedule for the
                year you select and computes:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Total MT tax</strong> – sum of tax in each bracket,
                  minus any credits you enter.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Marginal rate</strong> – the rate that applies to your
                  last dollar of taxable income.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Effective rate</strong> – total MT tax divided by your
                  pre-deduction income.
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                The “Bracket breakdown” table shows exactly how much of your
                income falls into each bracket and how much tax is generated
                there.
              </p>

              <h3>4. Take-home pay estimate</h3>
              <p>
                For a quick Montana-only view of your paycheck, we estimate:
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p>
                  <strong>Estimated take-home</strong> ≈ Income before
                  deductions − pre-tax deductions − MT income tax
                </p>
              </div>
              <p>
                This does <strong>not</strong> include federal income tax,
                Social Security, Medicare, or other payroll deductions. It is
                meant to isolate the impact of Montana state income tax.
              </p>

              <h2>Using the Montana income tax calculator effectively</h2>
              <h3>Compare filing statuses</h3>
              <p>
                If you are married, try switching between
                <strong>Married filing jointly</strong> and
                <strong>Married filing separately</strong> to see how your
                Montana tax changes. In many cases, joint filing results in a
                lower combined bill, but not always.
              </p>

              <h3>Test “what-if” scenarios</h3>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  Increase <strong>pre-tax deductions</strong> to see how
                  contributing more to a 401(k) or HSA can reduce your MT tax.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Toggle between <strong>standard</strong> and
                  <strong>itemized</strong> deductions to see which gives a
                  lower tax.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Add potential <strong>Montana tax credits</strong> (such as
                  energy or education credits) to see their direct
                  dollar-for-dollar impact.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h3>Limitations and assumptions</h3>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  Brackets and standard deduction amounts are modeled for recent
                  years and may not reflect future legislative changes.
                </li>
                <li>
                  The calculator does not handle every special Montana rule
                  (e.g., detailed pension exclusions, capital gains preferences,
                  or multi-state income apportionment).
                </li>
                <li>
                  Results are estimates only and are not tax or legal advice.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h2>Frequently asked questions about Montana income tax</h2>
              <h3>Is Montana a high-tax state?</h3>
              <p>
                Montana’s top marginal income tax rate is moderate compared with
                other states, and the state does not levy a general sales tax.
                However, property taxes and local factors can affect your
                overall tax burden.
              </p>

              <h3>Does Montana tax Social Security benefits?</h3>
              <p>
                Montana may tax a portion of Social Security benefits depending
                on your income level and filing status. The rules differ from
                federal treatment, so retirees should review the latest Montana
                guidance or consult a professional.
              </p>

              <h3>How often are Montana tax brackets updated?</h3>
              <p>
                Montana periodically adjusts its tax brackets and may change
                rates or the number of brackets through legislation. Always
                check the current-year tables from the Montana Department of
                Revenue when planning.
              </p>

              <h3>Can this calculator file my Montana tax return?</h3>
              <p>
                No. This tool is for planning and education only. To file, you
                will need official Montana forms, approved tax software, or a
                tax professional.
              </p>
            </section>
